Durban - KwaZulu Natal had the country's largest improvement in matric results the Minister of Basic Education announced yesterday.  The pass rate increased from 66.4% in 2016 to 72.8%, said Minister of Basic Education, Angie Motshekga, during a live TV broadcast on SABC on Thursday evening.  Today at 6am, scores of pupils received their individual matric results.  The national pass rate was 75,1%.  In KwaZulu Natal, Timera Naidoo from Port Shepstone High School,was placed first in the country for Physical Science.  The top performing province was Free State who achieved an 86.1% pass rate, and Eastern Cape achieved the lowest pass rate in the country with 65%.  Umgungundlovu was the top performing district in KwaZulu Natal with 81.5%; “We must agree that much has been achieved, but much more needs to be done in the areas of efficiency and quality. We call upon all South Africans to work together with us to move the public schooling to greater heights," said MEC Motshekga.  “Once again, I take off my hat to the Class of 2017, and I wish them the best in their future.  I believe that you will continue to shine wherever you are.”  The country’s 21 tops achievers were also recognized during the ceremony. They were awarded with prizes close to R3 million including bursaries, laptops and other equipment.  Joshua Chetty from Gauteng also took first place under the special education needs category. POST